Chapter 2 of Data Camp - Intro to Time Series Analsys

Trends: Variance

log()

  • Can linearize rapid growth
  • Can stabalize increasing variance

Only defined for positive values

diff()

Can remove the linear trend

With the seasonal difference option can remove the seasonal component diff(..., s)

rapid_growth = 500 + (seq(1, 40, length.out = 200) ^ 2) + (runif(200) * seq(1, 400, length.out=200))

par(mfrow=c(2,1))

ts.plot(rapid_growth)

linear_growth = log(rapid_growth)

ts.plot(linear_growth)

diff() takes the difference between each adjacent value. The result is always n -1 records. diff() can remove a time trend from a series.

Let’s see what happens when we apply to the linear_growth data.

diff_linear_growth = diff(linear_growth)
par(mfrow=c(2,1))
ts.plot(linear_growth)
ts.plot(diff_linear_growth)

For data with seasonality the lag= option can be applied to remove the seasonality. Let’s see what this can do.

rapid_growth_with_seasonality = rapid_growth + sin(1:200) * 100

par(mfrow=c(2, 1))
# smooth it
linear_growth_with_seasonality = log(rapid_growth_with_seasonality)
linear_growth_with_seasonality_no_trend = diff(linear_growth_with_seasonality)
ts.plot(rapid_growth_with_seasonality)
ts.plot(linear_growth_with_seasonality)

ts.plot(linear_growth_with_seasonality_no_trend)
ts.plot(diff(linear_growth_with_seasonality_no_trend, lag=6))

White Noise model

Simple examle of a stationary process.

The white noise process has:

  • A fixed, constant mean
  • A fixed, constant variance
  • No correlation over time

If any of these and possibly others, are true it is NOT WN

  • There is a trend in the data
  • There is periodocity in the data.
  • The variance is changing over time

The arima.sim() function can simulate a WN dataset. arima.sim(model=list(order=c(0,0,0)), n=50).

ARIMA

AutoRegressive Integrated Moving Average

The arima() function will display information about an ARIMA dataset including the mean (intercept), variance, standard error, etc.

These values can also be obtained directly with the mean() and var() functions.

wn1 = arima.sim(model = list(order=c(0,0,0)), n=50)
wn2 = arima.sim(model = list(order=c(0,0,0)), n=50, mean=100, sd=10)

par(mfrow=c(2,1))
ts.plot(wn1)
ts.plot(wn2)

arima(wn1, order=c(0,0,0))

Random Walk Time Series

  • No specified mean or variance
  • Strong dependance over time
  • Change or ingrements are WN

The Random Walk Model is recursively defined as:

Today = Yesteray + Noise

\(Y_t = Y_{t-1} + \epsilon_t\)

where \(\epsilon_t\) is mean zero white noise (WN) and \(\epsilon_t \longrightarrow \text{diff(Y)}\) is WN

  • Simulation requires and initial point \(Y_0\)
  • It has only 1 parm, the WN variance \(\sigma_{\epsilon}^2\)

The diff() of a Random Walk series is a White Noise series.

It can be defined to include a drift variable represented by \(c\)

\(Y_t = c + Y_{t-1} + \epsilon_t\)

A drift model has 2 parms, the WN variance \(\sigma_{\epsilon}^2\) and the constant \(c\). Which is just a Random Walk series with WN with mean \(c\).

The Random Walk series is teh cumulative sum (or integration) of a mean zero WN series. This is an ARIMA(0, 1, 0) model, where the middle 1 indicates the model’s order of integration is 1.

arima.sim() is used to create a Random Walk series with order=c(0,1,0).

random_walk = arima.sim(model=list(order=c(0,1,0)), n=100)

par(mfrow=c(1,2))

ts.plot(random_walk)

random_walk_diff = diff(random_walk)

ts.plot(random_walk_diff)

Now with drift

rwd = arima.sim(model=list(order=c(0,1,0)), n=100, mean=1)
par(mfrow=c(1,2))

ts.plot(rwd)

rwdd = diff(rwd)
ts.plot(rwdd)

model_wn <- arima(rwdd, order=c(0,0,0))
int_wn = coef(model_wn)

ts.plot(rwd)
abline(0, int_wn)

Stationarity

  • Stationary models are parsimonious
  • Have distributional stability over time

Observed time series:

  • Fluctuate randomly
  • But behave similarly from one time period to the next

See additional slides for more details

# Use arima.sim() to generate WN data
white_noise <- arima.sim(model=list(order=c(0,0,0)), n=100)

# Use cumsum() to convert your WN data to RW
random_walk <- cumsum(white_noise)
  
# Use arima.sim() to generate WN drift data
wn_drift <- arima.sim(model=list(order=c(0,0,0)), n=100, mean=0.4)
  
# Use cumsum() to convert your WN drift data to RW
rw_drift <- cumsum(wn_drift)

# Plot all four data objects
plot.ts(cbind(white_noise, random_walk, wn_drift, rw_drift))
